🚀 Antigravity Payments Blog: Infrastructure, Strategy, & Knowledge Base

Welcome to the central repository for my personal technical blog and payment strategy space. This repository serves as a fully containerized writing environment, housing my static HTML blog files, custom workspace configurations, editorial style guides, and an industry glossary.

As a Payments Product Leader, I use this space to bridge the gap between complex engineering realities (DevOps, ISO messaging, APIs) and strategic business drivers (regulatory frameworks, scheme economics, product localization).

💻 Local Development & Environment Setup

This project is configured to run in a customized development environment (using the Antigravity editor/VS Code framework) to ensure visual consistency and streamlined deployment.

1. Prerequisites & Tooling

Git: Ensure Git is installed globally on your machine.

Note on Non-Standard Paths: If installing on a partition or secondary drive (e.g., D: or Q:), ensure the installation path is added to your system's Environment Variables (PATH).

Editor: Optimized for VS Code / Antigravity editor ecosystems.

2. Local Identity Configuration

Before committing to this repository, set up your global Git signature to align with your public profile:

git config --global user.name "somabhagat"
git config --global user.email "bhagatsoma@gmail.com"



3. Integrated Terminal & IDE Path Alignment

To ensure the custom Git Bash terminal and source control integrations work seamlessly across varying local drive structures, the workspace relies on explicit JSON path mappings.

If your terminal shell or source control provider fails to locate Git automatically:

Access the command palette (Ctrl + Shift + P) and select "Preferences: Open User Settings (JSON)".

Map your local execution path to the git.path variable:

"git.path": "Q:\\Program Files\\Git\\bin\\git.exe"



In the workspace-specific configuration file (blog.code-workspace), verify the default terminal profile points directly to your shell binary:

"terminal.integrated.profiles.windows": {
    "Git Bash": {
        "path": "Q:\\Program Files\\Git\\bin\\bash.exe"
    }
}



📝 Contribution & Deployment Workflow

We maintain a clean, linear Git history. All updates to static pages, images, or assets should follow this standard workflow within the integrated Bash terminal.

# Step 1: Audit local changes and untracked assets
git status

# Step 2: Stage modified files
git add .

# Step 3: Commit with descriptive, imperative-mood messages
git commit -m "feat: implement S-curve diagram for transaction flow on PSD3 post"

# Step 4: Sync with remote repository
git push origin main



